    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"living constitution\" approach is fundamentally different from originalism, as it allows for a more flexible interpretation of the Constitution that evolves with society. Originalists argue that this approach undermines the stability and predictability of the law, as it can lead to interpretations that change with the prevailing political climate rather than adhering to the original text and intent. However, proponents of the living constitution argue that it allows the Constitution to remain relevant and responsive to contemporary issues. Ultimately, the debate hinges on whether one values a fixed interpretation of the Constitution or a dynamic one that adapts to changing societal norms.",
      "source": "target",
